    <h2 style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">Who’s behind this</h2>
    <p>
      I’m an HVAC professional with hands-on experience sizing, installing, and servicing residential systems.
      I built this calculator so families who don’t speak kilowatts all day can quickly get to a sensible starting point—before talking to a pro.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h2 style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">How the calculator works</h2>
    <ul style="padding-left:1.25rem; margin: .5rem 0;">
      <li>Uses typical <strong>running watts</strong> for common home loads and, where relevant, their <strong>starting (inrush) watts</strong>.</li>
      <li><strong>Air conditioning:</strong> run ≈ <code>1100&nbsp;W/ton</code> (standard) or <code>750&nbsp;W/ton</code> (inverter);
          startup ≈ <code>4.0×</code> (standard) or <code>1.5×</code> (inverter).
          If a soft-starter is toggled for a standard unit, we reduce surge by ~40%.</li>
      <li><strong>Managed loads:</strong> checking “I’ll manage loads” trims <em>non-AC running</em> by 20% to reflect staggered usage (AC running is unchanged).</li>
      <li><strong>Surge model:</strong> we take the <em>largest single start</em> and add it to the <em>running watts of everything else</em>, compare that to total running, and size to the higher number.</li>
      <li><strong>Custom extra surge:</strong> you can add a one-off temporary surge (defaults to 0&nbsp;W) for unique appliances.</li>
      <li><strong>Recommendation rule:</strong> we recommend a generator whose continuous rating keeps the calculated surge at ~<strong>80%</strong> of nameplate
          (≈<strong>125%</strong> headroom), then map to practical size tiers.</li>
    </ul>
    <p style="color:#666; margin-top:.5rem;">
      Note: AC surge per condenser is safety-capped in the model. Assumptions are periodically reviewed and adjusted as equipment standards evolve.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h2 style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">What this site is (and isn’t)</h2>
    <p>
      This is <strong>planning guidance</strong>, not a site survey. Homes vary, nameplates can surprise, and inrush currents can be quirky.
      Before purchasing or installing a generator, <strong>consult a licensed electrician/contractor</strong> to confirm sizing, transfer hardware, and code compliance.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section style="margin: 1.5rem 0;">
